<item>
            <title>[SEC-3190] RememberMe cookies cant handle username containing colon (&quot;:&quot;)</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-3190</link>
                <project id="10040" key="SEC">Spring Security</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;I have confirmed this issue with TokenBasedRememberMeServices.  The remember me cookie is a string of the form:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;username + &quot;:&quot; + expiryTime + &quot;:&quot; + Md5Hex(username + &quot;:&quot; + expiryTime + &quot;:&quot; + password + &quot;:&quot; + key)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is 3 tokens seperated by colons.  sample:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;doejohn:1767839462751:494b6435d6d0c2146bc608782543f805&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When the username contains a colon, which is the default with spring-social, cookie decoding fails as it encounters 4 tokens (splitting the username into 2 separate tokens).  sample:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;twitter:1705891096:1767839462751:494b6435d6d0c2146bc608782543f805&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It appears there is an existing hack to deal with urls containing colons (&quot;https://...&quot;) in AbstractRememberMeServices.decodeCookie().  I suggest urlencoding the value before creating the cookie string; and the url decoding the token when later retrieved from the cookie.&lt;/p&gt;



</description>
                <environment>spring security 4.0.3&lt;br/&gt;
spring social 1.1.4</environment>
